  "response": "According to our current understanding of physics, it is impossible for any object with mass to travel faster than the speed of light in a vacuum (approximately 299,792 kilometers per second). This limitation is a fundamental principle of Einstein's special relativity theory. The reasons include:\n\n1. As an object approaches the speed of light, its mass would theoretically increase towards infinity\n\n2. It would require infinite energy to accelerate a massive object to light speed\n\n3. The laws of physics, as we currently understand them, prevent matter from exceeding light speed\n\nHowever, some interesting phenomena exist:\n- Quantum entangement can appear to transmit information faster than light\n- Theoretical concepts like wormholes might allow apparent faster-than-light travel\n- The expansion of the universe can cause distant galaxies to move away from each other faster than light\n\nBut for any physical object with mass, faster-than-light travel remains impossible according to our current scientific knowledge.",
